		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Do you have the Sense of Obligation ?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18678'>Guillaume "FoRSaLe" Lestrelin</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18678&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 18, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> How i turned a little non-oscarized card into an entire shadow strategy : a corruption based on assignments.<br />
<br />
[A little Introduction]<br />
<br />
First of all, let me tell you how all this story began. When Black Rider was released, i was looking for some cards to upgrade my old classical Nazgul corruption deck. (something not good at all with the actual meta, but a shadow which gave me some pleasure to play with)<br />
<br />
While everybody was getting mad of Dark Approach, burning their old-fashioned Morgul Gates and building the new Nazguls-Love-the-Forest deck, i just noticed a poor uncommon condition that could improve my old stinky shadow. : Sense of Obligation.<br />
<br />
12U170<br />
[Sense of Obligation]<br />
RingWraith Condition<br />
Cost : 2<br />
text : &quot; To play, spot a RingWraith Minion. Bearer must be an unbound companion. Limit 1 per bearer. At the End of each assignment phase, if bearer is not assigned to a skirmish and a companion who does not bear a RingWraith condition is, add a burden.&quot;<br />
<br />
People often play this condition as i did first : we choose a poor companion not good for fight (like Sam or Derufin), we put a Sense of Obligation on him. And soon, the free people player have to choose between take a few more burdens and let his companion die to an overdose of fights.<br />
To play it this way, we basically put just one or two copies of Sense of Obligation in our deck, no more, because this card might be totally useless if more than 1 (maybe 2) copies are played at the same time.<br />
<br />
Still, there is another way.<br />
<br />
Sense of Obligation might become a deadly condition, even if played 3 or 4 times, when combined with some assignment power. The Combo is now simple and effective :<br />
<br />
10R68<br />
Ulaire Enquea, Thrall of the One<br />
ringwraith minion<br />
cost : 6<br />
strenght : 11<br />
vitality : 4<br />
site number : 3<br />
text : &quot;Enduring. Shadow cards cannont exert Ulaire Enquea during a skirmish phase. Skirmish : If Ulaire Enquea is skirmishing, heal him to add a burden.&quot;<br />
<br />
8R67<br />
Between Nazgul and Prey<br />
event.assignment<br />
cost : 4<br />
text : &quot;exert an enduring ringwraith minion twice to assign that minion to an unbound companion.&quot;<br />
<br />
Everybody knows this awesome combo (Enquea/BNaP) and nowadays, enduring nazguls is prolly one of the most dangerous shadows you can be confronted to. But what i have in mind, as you will see, is more an alternative fun version of it.<br />
<br />
[How to play it in Expanded format]<br />
<br />
As strong as this combo is, it won&#39;t make a whole deck by itself, we must find some other tricks to turn all this into something concrete. Here I propose some other cards to emphase the power of Sense of Obligation.<br />
<br />
1R236<br />
Ulaire Toldëa, Messenger of Morgul<br />
Ringwraith Minion<br />
cost : 6<br />
strenght : 12<br />
vitality : 3<br />
site number : 3<br />
text : &quot;Fierce. Assignment : Spot 4 burdens to assign a companion (except the ringbearer) to skirmish Ulaire Toldea.&quot;<br />
<br />
Toldea is so strong in this deck ! If You can spot 4 burdens (and this won&#39;t be too hard), you will be able to assign Toldea to any companion (except the RB of course). To be realistic, we can count on two Sense of Obligation in play near site 4 or 5, and something like four burdens so far. As Toldea is fierce, it will add something like 4 other burdens per site !<br />
<br />
2R75<br />
Bill Ferny, Swarthy Sneering Fellow<br />
RingWraith Minion<br />
Cost : 2<br />
Strenght : 4<br />
Vitality : 1<br />
Site number : 2<br />
Text : &quot;Nazgul are not roaming. The Free Peoples player may not assign a character to skirmish Bill Ferny. Discard Bill Ferny if underground.&quot;<br />
<br />
Since Bill&#39;s banishment is ended, we can use him again in expanded (although it is restricted) and it fits perfectly with our needs. Note that Bill can also be really annoying for alternative bearers because we can assign him to whoever we want.<br />
<br />
10R63<br />
Morgul Vanguard<br />
RingWraigth Minion<br />
cost : 6<br />
strenght : 12<br />
vitality : 3<br />
site number : 4<br />
text : &quot;Assignment : Assign this minion to an unbound companion bearing a hand weapon.&quot;<br />
<br />
As Morgul Vanguard is from the RingWraith culture, it can be spotted to play Sense of Obligation. Add to this its really nice assignment capability and we have a perfect dude for the job.<br />
<br />
11C120<br />
Entrapping Orc<br />
Orc Minion<br />
cost : 3<br />
strenght : 9<br />
vitality : 2<br />
site number : 4<br />
text : &quot;Assignment : Assign this minion to an unbound companion who has resistance 4 or less.&quot;<br />
<br />
Okay, this one is not a Morgul Orc, nor a Nazgul. But his assignment skill require nothing more than two burdens to be activated. And, as i will explain it later, he has the great quality to be weak !<br />
<br />
[Building the deck]<br />
<br />
Let&#39;s start with the obvious...<br />
<br />
Sense of Obligation x4 (of course)<br />
Ulaire Enquea, TotO x4<br />
Between Nazgul and Prey x4<br />
<br />
and now, just add<br />
<br />
Morgul Vanguard x3<br />
Ulaire Toldea, Messenger of Morgul x2<br />
Entrapping Orc x2<br />
Bill Ferny<br />
Morgul Squealer x2 (this can be helpfull to settle the trick)<br />
Ulaire Cantea, Black Assassin<br />
Keening Wail x3 (toil is as important as the burden added)<br />
All Blade Perish x3<br />
Drawn to its power x4 (the last touch)<br />
<br />
Job&#39;s done !<br />
<br />
Be carefull, this deck is not so easy to play.<br />
- drop 2 SoO (you know what i mean :) ) as soon as possible (no more)<br />
- prepare the enquea/bnap combo to put a large amout of burdens<br />
- play some other minions to add some, and finish with a toldea to corrupt the Ring-Bearer.<br />
<br />
In some cases, you can play very strange games, where the opponent try to kill his companion (the one who don&#39;t bear a sense of obligation), to counter your strategy (very fun :) That&#39;s why i recommend to never put more than 2 Sense of Obligation in play at the same time.<br />
Try to keep him alive as long as possible (isn&#39;t that stupid ?) to add a maximum of burdens, and when you have pump some Drawn to Its Power, let him die on your minions to add some more.<br />
This is where the weakness of the Entrapping Orc can serve you to keep opponent&#39;s companions alive, but skirmishing.<br />
<br />
[Other ways !]<br />
<br />
Of course, this is not the only way to play Sense of Obligation, and this is not even a serious one (but one that can still bring you some shadow wins and a lot of fun).<br />
<br />
Per example, i&#39;m sure we can do something with Desperate Defense of the Ring, Thin and Stretched, The Mouth of Sauron and Gorgoroth Assassin...<br />
Maybe not :)<br />
<br />
Anyway, i hope you liked my article (it&#39;s the first) and i let you show me some other fun ways to play LotR TCG. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=6101&view=1&PHPSESSID=c515b7a6c1c6143f06a503f2f261924c'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=c515b7a6c1c6143f06a503f2f261924c'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=c515b7a6c1c6143f06a503f2f261924c'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
